Security audit reveals 15 findings across the OWASP Top 10
The template’s security posture is its weakest dimension. In context, Bitsight’s TRACE
research (February 2026) found over 30,000 exposed OpenClaw instances with attackers
scanning for new deployments within minutes and targeting specific RPC method handlers.
Bitsight The Railway template’s design amplifies some of these risks.
CRITICAL findings
Command injection risk in the setup flow is the highest-priority concern. The wrapper
passes user-supplied values (API keys, bot tokens, provider names) to openclaw onboard -
-non-interactive as command-line arguments. If child_process.exec() is used instead
of child_process.spawn() with array arguments, shell metacharacters in any input field
( ; , | , $() , backticks) could achieve arbitrary code execution inside the container.
Without access to the exact source, this finding is inferred from architecture but represents
a CRITICAL risk that demands line-level verification.
Bootstrap script arbitrary execution is a second critical concern. The template supports a
/data/workspace/bootstrap.sh script that runs automatically on container startup.
GitHub Since the /data volume is persistent, an attacker who gains write access to the
volume (through any vulnerability) achieves persistent code execution that survives
redeploys.
HIGH findings
HTTP Basic auth with a single shared password protects the entire /setup wizard,
GitHub debug console, device pairing, config editor, and (optionally) the web terminal.
Basic auth transmits credentials as Base64-encoded plaintext in every request, cached by
the browser with no logout mechanism. The documentation explicitly says “the username
field is ignored.” GitHub Railway Combined with zero rate limiting on authentication
attempts, this is vulnerable to online brute-force. The local testing instructions ( docker run
... -e SETUP_PASSWORD=test ) GitHub encourage weak passwords. GitHub
Weak or auto-generated gateway tokens compound the auth weakness. The
OPENCLAW_GATEWAY_TOKEN is documented as optional — “if not set, the wrapper generates
one (not ideal).” GitHub GitHub No complexity requirements exist; even single-character
tokens are accepted. This single token gates full gateway access including AI agent control,
message history, and tool execution.
The web terminal ( /tui ) provides full container shell access behind only the same
Basic auth password. When ENABLE_WEB_TUI=true , the /tui endpoint runs openclaw tui
interactively in the browser GitHub via a PTY. GitHub No additional authentication, MFA,
or IP allowlisting protects this effectively unlimited shell access.
No CSRF protection exists for any /setup/api/* endpoint. Since Basic auth credentials
are automatically attached by the browser to cross-origin requests, a malicious page visited
by an authenticated user could trigger setup changes, approve bot pairings, initiate config
exports, or execute doctor commands without the user’s knowledge.
MEDIUM findings
The audit identified nine additional MEDIUM-severity issues: exposed debug endpoints
( /setup/api/debug reveals internal filesystem paths), GitHub Docker containers likely
running as root, unencrypted credentials stored on the volume, CORS configuration gaps for
custom domains, WebSocket origin validation bypass via the localhost proxy pattern, input
validation gaps for API keys and bot tokens, dependency supply chain risks from building
OpenClaw from source at deploy time, implicit trust of upstream OpenClaw binaries, and
potentially timing-unsafe password comparison.
