Reliability gaps create real operational pain
Real-world reliability issues are well-documented across Railway Help Station, GitHub
issues, and community forums. The canonical repo has 8 open issues github and
community support threads reveal recurring patterns.
“Gateway not ready” is the most common failure mode, reported repeatedly on Railway
Help Station. Root causes include stale PID lock files (container PID reuse in Docker causes
the new gateway to detect a “running” instance via the old lock ClawKit — fixed in
OpenClaw 2026.1.23 but older pinned versions remain vulnerable), ClawKit config file
corruption (often caused by the AI agent itself modifying its own config), Railway and
invalid channel configurations that cause silent gateway startup failures. Railway
Message delivery replay after restart is a confirmed bug (OpenClaw #29106). When the
gateway restarts, the delivery-recovery system replays already-delivered messages to
recipients — messages sent days or weeks ago resurface as duplicates. The root cause is a
race between delivery and acknowledgment file removal during shutdown. GitHub
Graceful shutdown behavior is uncertain. The wrapper spawns the gateway as a child
process, but signal propagation (SIGTERM → child) could not be verified from available
documentation. If SIGTERM is not properly forwarded, the gateway may be killed mid-
operation, compounding the delivery replay bug. Railway’s volume-attached services
experience mandatory downtime during redeploys GitHub (to prevent concurrent mount
corruption). Railway
No monitoring, alerting, or structured logging exists. No Prometheus metrics endpoint,
no external monitoring integration, no log rotation for the gateway logs on the volume
(which grow indefinitely). Logs appear to be plaintext rather than structured JSON. The only
monitoring option is the third-party commercial tool ClawKit, which pings instances every
30 seconds. ClawKit
Testing is virtually nonexistent
The testing posture is the most significant quality risk across the entire template
ecosystem. The arjunkomath fork — and the vast majority of the 200+ forks — contain zero
test files, zero CI/CD pipelines, and zero code quality tooling. No ESLint, no Prettier, no
TypeScript, no .editorconfig . The CLAUDE.md file in the repo suggests AI-assisted
development, which without tests creates compounding quality risk.
Only the canonical vignesh07 repo maintains a test/ directory and GitHub Actions
workflows, but test scope and coverage are unknown. For a template that handles
authentication, reverse-proxying, process management, and sensitive credential storage,
the absence of integration tests for proxy behavior, shutdown paths, health check accuracy,
and auth bypass scenarios is a HIGH severity gap.
The frontend setup wizard works but lacks polish
The setup wizard serves its core purpose — enabling non-technical users to configure
OpenClaw without CLI access — but falls short on accessibility, mobile experience, and error
handling. The UI is vanilla HTML/CSS/JS with no framework, which provides broad browser
compatibility but limited interactivity.
Accessibility is completely unaddressed. No ARIA labels, no screen reader support, no
focus management in dialogs, no aria-live regions for dynamic status updates, no
documented keyboard navigation, and no WCAG compliance testing. The HTTP Basic auth
dialog with an “ignored username” field creates confusion for all users GitHub GitHub is particularly problematic for assistive technology users.
